<title>Roadrunner roadmap</title>




<div class=3D"wrapper">
    <div class=3D"container">
        <div class=3D"image">
            <img src=3D"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/guotata1996/guota=
ta1996.github.io/master/assets/img/post5/side.png" alt=3D"Vertical Image">
        </div>
        <div class=3D"text">
            <h1>Roadrunner roadmap</h1>
            <h2>General API design</h2>
                <p> Xodr format is complicated and hard to deal with direct=
ly. We therefore introduce the intuitive concept of "road profile".
                  </p><li>To make things simpler, it only supports fixed-wi=
dth driving lanes. (no sidewalks, no shoulders)</li>
                  <li>Lane section can be simplified as number of lanes &am=
p; divider width (zero, half-lane, full-lane, etc.)</li>
                  <li>Two-way roads have 2 road profiles for each lane sect=
ion; one-way roads have only 1.</li>
                  <li>Ref lines are modeled as defined by xodr, but we can =
start with line + cubic spline only.</li>
                <p></p>
            <h2>xodr exporter</h2>
                <p> Before any UI was developed, the only way to visualize =
stuff is through <a href=3D"https://odrviewer.io/">online openDrive viewer<=
/a>
                    Thus, the first modification to <a href=3D"https://gith=
ub.com/pageldev/libOpenDRIVE">libOpenDRIVE</a> is the ability to export to =
xodr.
                </p>
            <h2>Road profile -&gt; xodr road converter</h2>
                <p>An algorithm that converts the easy-to-understand {lengt=
h:roadProfile} dict representation to xodr format that requires
                    </p><li>Continuous lane border / width change</li>
                    <li>Well-defined linkage (successor/predecessor) for ea=
ch lane</li>
                    <li>Unit test: 100+ random-generated profiles to be con=
verted.</li>
                    <li>Results are automatically checked for errors.</li>
                <p></p>
            <h2>Generate junction from incoming road info</h2>
                <p>On a high level, a junction is basically a set of connec=
ting roads, plus any traffic rules like signal phase.
                    Given the full details of incoming &amp; outgoing roads=
, we have to ensure that:
                    </p><li>All incoming lanes have at least one successor =
connecting road</li>
                    <li>No connecting roads cross each other unless they ha=
ve to.</li>
                    <li>Error out if these conditions cannot be satisfied</=
li>
                <p></p>
                <p> There's also a test suit of 100+ cases, each consisting=
 of 3 to 6 incoming roads with random profiles,
                    to test the robustness of the algorithm.
                   Currently, users have no option to modify the junction o=
nce it's generated. This is a planned feature for the future.</p>
            <h2>Road graphics as QGraphicsItem</h2>
                <p>This step marks an important turning point: we can final=
ly view the map right in a Qt graphical interface!
                    With Qt's QGraphicsScene and QGraphicsView, it's pretty=
 easy to get a 2D view of the map going.
                    We just need to flip the Y axis of the view by defining=
 zoom to (1, -1) to overcome the difference in the coordinate system.
                </p>
            <h2>Road operations: split, join, reverse</h2>
                <p>To make our way towards graphical road editing, we need =
to move our API to a higher level.
                    </p><li>Operating on road means operating on both ref l=
ine and lane profile.</li>
                    <li>Split arises from the need of forming a junction.</=
li>
                    <li>Join is essential for extending an existing road.</=
li>
                    <li>Reverse does nothing visible but change the ref lin=
e direction.=20
                        It's turns the task of joining "A-&gt;B and C-&gt;B=
" to "A-&gt;B and B-&gt;C", which is more straightforward.</li>
                <p></p>
                <p>Extra caution should be given to corner cases, like a re=
f line is split at a neglectable distance (1mm) from its end.=20
                    We put a limit on the minimum length of ref line and la=
ne section to avoid numerical issues.
                </p>
            <h2>Draw ref lines</h2>
                <p>Since we only allow line + cubic spline for now, the log=
ic to define ref line is simple:
                    </p><li>1st click defines the starting point. This can =
be another road's (existing) end point.</li>
                    <li>2nd click defines the control point. If both clicks=
 are on existing endpoints, simply connect them and we are done</li>
                    <li>3rd click defines the endpoint, as well as the star=
ting point of the next segment.=20
                        This can be combined with the 2nd click (into a dou=
ble-click) to form a straight line.</li>
                    <li>In fact in most cases we are creating quadratic spl=
ine rather than cubic, except the former generates weird geometry.</li>
                <p></p>
                <p>Cubic spline works fine in most cases including junction=
s, but it's hard to draw the circular shape of roundabouts and=20
                    complicated interchanges. Fortunately, OpenDRIVE suppor=
ts arcs and spirals, marking an important direction of improvement.
                </p>
            <h2>Localization in road coordinate system</h2>
                <p>Localization means finding the road at a 2D point (or ar=
ea), and where are we at inside its local (s, t) coordinate system,=20
                    i.e. what's the closest point on its ref line, and whic=
h lane we are on.
                </p>
                <p> Of course we can develop a formula or iterative algorit=
hm to calculate this directly,=20
                    but it's not easy to gain full robustness given the var=
ious parametrized curves we are dealing with.
                    Not to mention as such a frequently-called function (at=
 each frame the cursor is moved!),
                    we have to carefully limit its execution/iteration time=
 or the cursor could feel laggy.
                </p>
                <p> Thanks to the spatial query API by QGraphicsScene, it's=
 much simpler if we deal with this in a discrete manner.
                    We divide each lane into fine-grained rectangle-like po=
lygons, each of which stores its position in local coordinate system.
                    By asking Qt which polygon we are at, we get a rough es=
timate of our answer, which can be further improved by interpolation.
                </p>
                <p>
                    This method benefits us a lot when computing the overla=
pping area of two roads, by collecting all overlapping pieces of polygons
                    and gluing them together (where MultiSegment helper cla=
ss is used for).=20
                    It not only provides the intersecting point of two ref =
lines, but also the entire area where a junction is needed,=20
                    depending on the local width and curvature of each road=
.
                </p>
            <h2>Form junctions while drawing roads</h2>
                <p> With the localization technique in place, drawing junct=
ions is as simple as 1,2 and 3:
                    </p><li>Determine the section of roads that overlap as =
(s1, s2), with some margin left.</li>
                    <li>Cut each road to (0, s1), (s2, Length). If either s=
ection vanishes form a T-junction. Abort if both vanish.</li>
                    <li>Call junction generation API defined earlier to cal=
culate connecting roads.</li>
                <p></p>
            <h2>Incremental road graphics </h2>
                <p> With any of the operations we do to roads (split, join,=
 reverse), the road itself changes or vanishes,=20
                    but there's absolutely no need to re-create its graphic=
al representation (QGraphicsItem), because it's expensive!
                    We can easily afford to create the QGraphicsItems for a=
 100-meter road, but what if user extends it 100 times?
                    By the end of day we will repeat the work above for 1+2=
+...+100 =3D 5050 times, but only the last 100 count. That's 98% wasted!
                </p>
                <p> Therefore, we must be more careful about how we handle =
a road's graphics during those operations.=20
                    For instance, with a "join B to A" operation we can sim=
ply std::move most pieces of B to A,=20
                    with the exception of the join point where certain leng=
th of transition needs to be generated.
                </p>
                <p> This results in an important property: time complexity =
of any single edit won't grow linearly with map size.
                    Of course, as a common practice we still have to limit =
the length of new roads created at a time (currently 500 meters)=20
                    to prevent the UI from temporarily freezing.
                </p>
           =20
            <h2>Add road to existing junction</h2>
                <p> Convenience feature to turns a T junction into an X jun=
ction.=20
                    Just draw a road that overlaps with any existing connec=
ting road of one or two existing junction(s).</p>
            <h2>Save/Load, Undo/Redo with ChangeTracker</h2>
                <p> With the number of features (and bugs!) introduced so f=
ar, we need something that can easily bring us to an earlier state,
                    either due to a bug that causes crash, or a misclick re=
sulting in some unwanted changes.
                </p>
                <p> At the end of each successful operation that made chang=
e to the map, ChangeTracker records and serializes the actual changes=20
                    (currently, any added / deleted / modified road &amp; j=
unction xml node) and apply them to the maintained (serializable) xodr map.
                    The changes are also stored in the undo/redo stack, whi=
ch are then used for undo/redo.
                </p>
                <p> The existence of a continuously-maintained serializable=
 map is a key feature that didn't exist in RoadBuilder.=20
                    As a bi-directionally convertible twin of what's happen=
ing inside the scene, objects are referred to and linked by=20
                    string/int IDs as opposed to pointers. These are like t=
wo sides of a coin:
                    </p><li>We still need smart pointers to store objects r=
elationship, as they require minimum care of life cycle</li>
                    <li>ID-based linkage is readily serializable and reliab=
ly reflects the state of program, making it easy to store and recover.</li>
                <p></p>
                <p> The cost of maintaining this pair of twins, obviously, =
is that we must always ensure their consistency.=20
                    That's the purpose of the following feature.
                </p>
            <h2>Verification at every moment</h2>
                <p> Unit testing works well for complex logic blocks whose =
input can be easily defined and randomized.=20
                    In addition, we need integration tests that check how t=
hose building blocks work together as a whole.
                    However, it's much more costly to maintain hard-coded t=
est cases: as the feature set evolves,=20
                    so does the expected output of a given input. Updating =
those expectations requires a lot of manual work.
                </p>
                <p> Then what about letting the program test itself? In the=
 context of a map editor, it translates to=20
                    "let the program check if what's drawn matches what's s=
erialized". The most common check we perform is that, if two lanes are supp=
osed
                    to be predecessor/successor, then they must meet at abo=
ut the same point (with 1cm tolerance due to numerical inaccuracy). There a=
re
                    quite a few similar checks throughout the "verification=
" process; any violation will cause an exception to be thrown.
                </p>
                <p> More importantly, this verification is by default perfo=
rmed at the scope of the entire map, at the moment of every change. This ma=
kes=20
                    sure every bug/inconsistency immediately comes to our a=
ttention at the earliest moment, and we cannot easily get away without fixi=
ng it.
                    As a development-assisting feature, I also decided to i=
nclude this in the production version, although turned off by default, so t=
hat
                    anyone can report bugs and help improve the software if=
 they want to.
                </p>
            <h2>Lane section profile editing widget</h2>
                <img src=3D"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/guotata1996/g=
uotata1996.github.io/master/assets/img/post5/profile_editing_widget.JPG">
                <p>
                    Flexible lane section profile definition is an importan=
t feature unique to RoadRunner.=20
                    Instead of letting user choose from a collection of pre=
-defined profiles, this widget uses two draggable horizontal bars and=20
                    four vertical handles to let one decide how many lanes =
to create on the left and right sides, and how much space to leave for the =
divider.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The boundary dark/light background is where the ref lin=
e lies. While normally the ref line lies right in the middle of the cross s=
ection,=20
                    it's allowed to put more lanes on one side than the oth=
er, creating shifting lanes without bending the ref line.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In addition to manually dragging those bars and handles=
, one can also pick from the previous profile by right-clicking=20
                    (and dragging) on any existing road.
                </p>
            <h2>Highlight hovering display</h2>
                <p>
                    When hovering, a road is highlighted with the following=
 information displayed:
                    </p><li>Road ID</li>
                    <li>Length along ref line and lane ID</li>
                    <li>Ref line direction</li>
                <p></p>
                <p>To see more details on the console regarding road profil=
e and junction info, press key I.</p>
                <p>If multiple roads are overlapping at the spot, press key=
 A to cycle highlight among them.</p>
            <h2>Make ramps in Lane mode</h2>
                <p>By far, multi-lane roads are drawn as a whole, while lan=
e distribution in junctions is calculated automatically.
                   This might be okay for 19th century traffic, but it's in=
capable of defining highway ramps, which are everywhere in modern cities.
                </p>
                <p>We will need a new mode for this: Lane mode. Inheriting =
most functions from the existing road drawing modes, the key feature in thi=
s mode
                    is extending from / merging into individual lane(s), ra=
ther than roads as a whole. In other words, in this mode, one needs to conf=
igure
                    exactly how many lanes he wants to go out of/into an in=
terface, because no transition will be automatically made.
                </p>
                <p>On OpenDRIVE's side, direct junction, which is natually =
used for making ramps, comes in handy. There's no connecting road anymore,=
=20
                    because roads are directly connected with each other fr=
om the moment they are created.
                </p>
                <p>Although seemingly simpler than the other road drawing m=
ode, lane mode is a big step in the overall development and took about a fu=
ll month.=20
                    Since no junction is automatically generated when roads=
 are extended in this mode, we get a small perk that allows creation of "br=
idges",
                    before the concept of 3rd dimension is formally introdu=
ced.
                </p>
            <h2>U-turn</h2>
                <p>The dead end is annoying for traffic simulation, as cars=
 can get stuck and have nowhere to go. With the introduction of lane mode, =
luckily,
                    there's an elegant solution: a U-turn is basically a ra=
mp that leaves and enters the same road!=20
                    Just by two clicks a U-turn is made, eliminating a dead=
 end.
                </p>
            <h2>Basic traffic demo</h2>
                <p>Although not being a key feature of a map editor, runnin=
g some traffic is still a good side task because:
                    </p><li>It verifies the correctness of the generated na=
vigation graph.</li>
                    <li>It confirms that RoadRunner-exported maps can poten=
tially be used in traffic simulators.</li>
                    <li>It's just cool by looking at cars running on hand-d=
rawn roads!</li>
                <p></p>
                <p>For now, traffic simulation is really just the minimum: =
cars run at constant speed;=20
                    there's no collision check so cars can run into each ot=
her; cars won't switch lanes; there's no traffic rules, etc.=20
                    Static navigation map is created when simulation starts=
, and simulation is automatically canceled once user switches to road editi=
ng mode.
                </p>
            <h2>Action recording</h2>
                <p>Heading into July, preparation begins for the public rel=
ease. Releasing a piece of software means I have to make sure there's very =
little bugs or=20
                    crashes, at least during normal workflow(i.e. user isn'=
t intentionally breaking it). As a reliable developer, I must test and fix =
the software myself
                    to a point where I can confidently play around for with=
out triggering a bug.
                </p>
                <p>But one difficulty I encountered is that certain bugs ea=
sily slip away as soon as they appear. For example, a crash is encountered =
after 10 minutes
                    of testing, during which 5km of roads have been created=
. It's nearly impossible to recall or recognize the action sequence that le=
ads to the crash.
                    Even if I can, some bugs (especially precision-related =
ones) require precise mouse clicks to appear, and can't be easily repeated =
manually.
                </p>
                <p>The only way out of this situation is storing everything=
 user did to the UI, and being able to replay the full action (QEvent) sequ=
ence.=20
                    To make things easier to control and get us focused on =
the map widget, rather than directly recording actions at the Application l=
evel,=20
                    events inside maps editor are recorded as-is, while the=
 rest are abstracted -- we directly store the final output of those actions=
,=20
                    (under the context of lane profile widget: new lane pro=
file &amp; offset), rather than the entire action sequence (how bars and ha=
ndles are dragged).
                </p>
                <p>This approach certainly has some cons: once a new widget=
 is added we must also implement its version record/replay to capture the w=
ay it affects the
                    program. On the other hand, recording at the Applicatio=
n level could be tricker, because of Qt's complicated event processing syst=
em, not to even=20
                    mention the case when multiple windows are active.
                    It's still an open question how to reliably record/repl=
ay all events of interest under Qt framework.
                </p>
            <h2>Action replay verification</h2>
                <p>How do we confirm that action recording/replay is reliab=
le, i.e. replay always honestly reproduces what was recorded?=20
                    With the introduction of new features, how do we know i=
f anything breaks it / when it needs to be updated?
                </p>
                <p>Naturally, we can compare the result of original editing=
, vs the result of replayed actions, by comparing the xodr maps they export=
.=20
                    If the recorded action sequence is accurate, every sing=
le character should exactly match.</p>
                <p>I decided to push this one step further by baking this p=
rocess into the program. Every time the application quits,=20
                    the process above is executed automatically (to save ti=
me, users are welcome to turn it off in preferences). If any difference is =
detected in the=20
                    output maps, an error will be printed in the console po=
inting to the bad record and two versions of maps. Otherwise, those three f=
iles will be removed.
                    This kind of issue shall be attended to with high prior=
ity because the record/replay mechanism is effectively a built-in debugger.
                </p>
            <h2>Action replay window</h2>
                <p> After action recording was completed, I initially made =
action replay as simple as a for loop that replays everything loaded from a=
 record.
                    This worked without any issue in theory, but in practic=
e it's annoying to use because of the long blocking time inside the main th=
read.=20
                    Since the UI is frozen, I knew nothing about the progre=
ss and can't even cancel. This is not tolerable even during development sta=
ge.
                </p>
                <p> I finally made up my mind to invest a few days in makin=
g a dialog where I can track, control and quit the replay process. This dia=
log is modal so that
                    the main window is blocked from receiving any events, e=
nsuring the replay sequence isn't contaminated. A QTimer is used internally=
 to fire off replay
                    orders, one after another.
                </p>
                <p> Although simple, this window provides quite a few desir=
able features that synergize well with the rest of the editor:
                    </p><li>If user wants to terminate action replay verifi=
cation, he can just click the quit button on the window.</li>
                    <li>By using recorded time delay between actions to rep=
lay, user can watch how a map was created in a natural playback speed, just=
 like
                        a watching screen recording. Plus, saving and shari=
ng a replay is way more convenient than recording the screen and sharing th=
e video.
                    </li>
                    <li>By introducing break points, one can easily pause t=
he replay at any point he wants.</li>
                <p></p>
                <p> With the completion of the record/replay mechanism, the=
 error handling workflow is also redesigned to treat each level of error in=
 our best interest.
                    This will be discussed in more detail in a separate pos=
t.
                </p>
            <h2>Preparing for release</h2>
                <p> To this point, RoadRunner is largely feature-frozen for=
 its first public release. All the rest is miscellaneous window/menu adjust=
ments, visual improvements,=20
                    and bug fixes. With the action record/replay mechanism,=
 most time when a verification error or crash is encountered, I could keep =
modifying the code and=20
                    replaying the saved action sequence until the issue's g=
one -- each retry taking less than a minute including the compile time.=20
                    In practice, most errors are resolved in an hour or so,=
 a huge improvement over RoadBuilder's development.=20
                    A good example of investing in a handy tool that almost=
 immediately pays off.
                </p>
                <p> As a special mention, qrc saved my life when importing =
icons to replace plain text on buttons.=20
                    I was able to fully focus on looking for / making these=
 resources without worrying about whether they can be correctly displayed.<=
/p>
            <h2>Ubuntu version</h2>
                <p> While all work has been done on Windows so far, making =
an Ubuntu version is almost a free add-on given all the dependencies and to=
olchains are cross-platform.
                    In practice, adapting to Ubuntu still took me half a da=
y, mostly due to the difference in file system and UI appearance. For insta=
nce, the replay window
                    cannot be moved around in Ubuntu and spawns right in th=
e center, blocking most of the view. Some default font sizes are also very =
different,=20
                    rendering texts invisible. After resolving a dozen smal=
l issues like this, all core functionalities are available to use on both p=
latforms.
                </p>
                <p> I can see an efficiency increase in both build time and=
 frame rate with Linux cxx build toolchain, compared to MSVC compiler.=20
                    However, as primarily a user interface I still prefer t=
o have it on Windows which greatly boosts the overall user experience.
                    Thus, my future development will still be happening on =
and targeting Windows, but I will ensure the availability of core functiona=
lities on Ubuntu.=20
                </p>
        </div>
    </div>
   =20
